{"key":"processedPost-9662713","value":{"id":9662713,"first":9662593,"last":9663991,"when":1232692928,"utime":"01/23/09 08:42 AM","content":"Get the verm damp so that if you squeeze a handful really hard, only a few drops come out.&nbsp; Pasteurize or even sterilize the verm, and then I'd suggest mixing the verm with the fully colonized grains, rather than trying to make a casing layer with it.&nbsp; Mix the verm and grains, and then cover the tray with aluminum foil for a week to ten days so the verm can fully colonize.&nbsp; At that point, expose to fruiting conditions.<br />I'd suggest a plastic tray, or line the aluminum tray with plastic.&nbsp; Mycelium metabolites will eat right through aluminum, and if it opens up holes as shown in the picture below, it will encourage bottom pinning due to the air exchange in an area where you don't want it.<br />RR<br /><a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/07-45/456009399-Aluminum_shiitake_tray.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/07-45/456009399-thumb_Aluminum_shiitake_tray.jpg\"></a>","title":"Re: How moist should verm be for casing grain?"}}